-- Regression: REG-02 crash-canary for closure capture of mutable state.
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 37-02's collect_mono_enums_node
-- walker crashed on if/elif/else lowering because of a locally-
-- shadowed struct typedef. Closure-with-capture is structurally
-- different from a bare lambda: the walker must recurse into the
-- captured_names[] array AND the closure body, and the lowered LIR
-- materializes a closure environment struct + a malloc site for the
-- environment. Walker cases that handle CLOSURE but fail to recurse
-- into the capture list produce an empty environment at runtime,
-- silently reading zero for every captured variable. Phase 67-02
-- added an iron_oom_abort guard on the closure-env malloc path, and
-- Phase 66 added -Werror=switch-enum globally; this canary is the
-- runtime regression net for the capture-list dispatch path.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.** A capturing closure lowers to
--   ClosureEnv { captured_a, captured_b, ... }  (heap-allocated)
--   + Iron_FuncDecl { is_lambda=true, captured_names=[a, b, ...] }
-- Walker cases that fail to recurse into captured_names drop the
-- environment slots; cases that fail to recurse into the body drop
-- every statement inside the closure. The resulting silent-wrong
-- output is exactly the "passes compile, wrong at runtime" failure
-- mode the Phase 37-02 bug caused.
--
-- **Fix Summary.** Phase 67-08 added this fixture as a REG-02 crash
-- canary. Uses the `var count = 0` + `count += 1` inside closure
-- pattern (see tests/integration/capture_02_mutate.iron and
-- capture_20_game_state.iron for the canonical templates).
-- CI integration: runs in both Debug and Release via Phase 66-04's
-- build-and-test-release job.
--
-- **Severity.** H (regression potential) -- captures are exercised
-- by every stateful callback / game-state Iron program, so a walker
-- regression would produce silent wrong output on real code.

func main() {
  var count = 0
  val bump = func() { count += 1 }
  bump()
  bump()
  bump()
  bump()
  bump()
  println("count: {count}")
}
